Analyzing which factors impact credit score the most and how to classify data into a credit score¶

Predicting a person's credit card score is important because it can help financial institutions make informed decisions about who to lend money to. By using a classifier with the ability to predict credit card scores, financial institutions can more accurately assess an individual's creditworthiness and determine important things such as their likelihood of repaying a loan. This can help the institution make more informed lending decisions, which can ultimately reduce their financial risk and improve their overall profitability. Additionally, a classifier with this ability can be useful for individuals as well, as it can help them understand their own creditworthiness and make more informed financial decisions. The goal of this project is to identify trends and to create a model that can accurately classify people into credit score groups.

Cleaning the data¶

Here we want to eliminate columns of the dataframe in order to prevent our model from taking into account factors that don't matter. For example, something like ID isn't something we want the model to know because it may think that there is value in the number that we assign the person. For reasons similiar to this we also remove customer ID, month, name, and SSN.

Now that we only have the data needed for the project. We have to clean up the data to have accurate information only. For example, we don't want things such as "age: -500". We have to do things such as remove extra dashes and change the type of certain columns. This is done for several columns, all with their own issues within thier data.

In [ ]:
# amount invested monthly
training["Amount_invested_monthly"] = training["Amount_invested_monthly"].replace( "__10000__", 10000.00)
training["Amount_invested_monthly"] = training["Amount_invested_monthly"].astype("float64")
# monthly balance
training["Monthly_Balance"] = training["Monthly_Balance"].replace("__-333333333333333333333333333__", 0)
training["Monthly_Balance"] = training["Monthly_Balance"].astype("float64")
#delayed payment
training["Num_of_Delayed_Payment"] = training["Num_of_Delayed_Payment"].str.replace(r"_$", "", regex=True)
training["Num_of_Delayed_Payment"] = training["Num_of_Delayed_Payment"].astype("float64")
#annual income
training["Annual_Income"] = training["Annual_Income"].str.replace(r"_$", "", regex=True)
training["Annual_Income"] = training["Annual_Income"].astype("float64")
#age
training["Age"] = training["Age"].str.replace(r"_$", "", regex=True)
training["Age"] = training["Age"].astype("int64")
training["Age"] = training["Age"].apply(lambda x: x if x > 0 and x < 115 else np.nan)
# Occupation
training["Occupation"] = training["Occupation"].replace("_______", np.nan)
# payment behavior
training["Payment_Behaviour"] = training["Payment_Behaviour"].replace("!@9#%8", "Medium_spent_Medium_value_payments")
# number of loans
training["Num_of_Loan"] = training["Num_of_Loan"].str.replace(r"_$", "", regex=True)
training["Num_of_Loan"] = training["Num_of_Loan"].astype("int64")
training["Num_of_Loan"] = training["Num_of_Loan"].apply(lambda x:  x if x >= 0 else np.nan)
# credit mix
training["Credit_Mix"] = training["Credit_Mix"].replace("_", "")
training["Credit_Mix"] = training["Credit_Mix"].replace("-", "")
# changing credit limit
training["Changed_Credit_Limit"] = training["Changed_Credit_Limit"].replace("_", 0)
training["Changed_Credit_Limit"] = training["Changed_Credit_Limit"].astype("float64")
# drop duplicate ids
training.drop_duplicates(subset="ID", inplace=True)
training = training.drop(columns ="ID")
#get values out of "credit history age"
training["Credit_History_Age"] = training["Credit_History_Age"].str.extract(r'(\d+)')
training["Credit_History_Age"] = training["Credit_History_Age"].replace(np.nan, 0)
# deletes the row if age or num is NaN
training = training.dropna(subset=["Age", "Num_of_Loan"])
# outstanding debts
training["Outstanding_Debt"] = training["Outstanding_Debt"].str.replace(r"_$", "", regex=True)

Now that the data has been preprocessed and cleaned, we are ready to move on to the next phase of the analysis: exploratory data analysis. This is an important step that allows us to gain a better understanding of the data and identify any patterns or trends that may be present. We will now be looking at how certain variables may affect the classification of an individual's credit score. In other words, we will be trying to identify which variables are most important for predicting an individual's credit score. This is important for us to know because this will ultimately be the factor that allows us to create an accurate classifier.

Data Exploration¶

On first thought, the immediate idea is to create a graph with all the variables and see which has the highest correlation

Looking at the above graphs, we can see a few things. There is a higher percentage of people with "Standard" credit scores in the ages between 18 and 45 than before 18 and after 45. Occupation seemed to have no impact on what credit score you will have, with each of the different occupations having around the same number of people in the poor, standard, and good rankings. Lawyers had a very slight increase in the amount of "good", but it is not significant enough to draw any conclusion from. However, in the third graph, we can see that having a better credit mix does seem to correlate to having a better credit score category. It seems that low spending and small value payments leads to a higher number of standard and good credit scores, so this may be a behavior to possibly be on the look out for. This also may just be a common practice because it also yielded the most "poor" score too.

We now have a better idea on how some categorical variables impact credit score classifications. We should take a look at some of the other numerical variables and how they correlate to credit scores. These give a concrete idea of which variables may be more important than others.

In these graphs we can see a lot of interesting things. In the final plot, we can see that the more you use a credit card, in general you have a a better credit score. The other graphs that I didn't mention either didn't convey a difference in behaviors, or the difference was too small to be conclusive.

Now that we have a better idea of how our data works and what variables may have the most impact on a credit score grouping, we are almost ready to move to the next step, creating a classifier. First, we have to transform all our categorical values into numerical ones so that sklearn can create the classifier. We can do this by one hot encoding our categorical values. We will also drop all rows with NaN since RandomForestClassifier does not accept missing values encoded as NaN natively.

Preparing for creating a classifier¶

In [ ]:
# One hot encoding training
training = training.dropna()
training = pd.get_dummies(training, columns=["Occupation", "Type_of_Loan", "Credit_Mix", "Payment_of_Min_Amount","Payment_Behaviour"])

We are now going to train our classifier to attempt to decide what kind of credit score someone has based on thier data. We are going to start with a random forest classifier since this usually yields postive results and is a good way to prevent overfitting.

Creating our classifier¶

In [ ]:
# label is the label that we are giving each observation
label = training["Credit_Score"]

training = training.drop("Credit_Score", axis=1) # we need to drop the label group before we pass in the data

# get the groups
xtrain, xtest, ytrain, ytest = train_test_split(training, label, test_size=0.2, random_state=1)

# Train the random forest classifier
forest = RandomForestClassifier()
forest.fit(xtrain, ytrain)

Analyzing our classifiers results¶

Lets take a look at how well our classifier did. We hope to see high accuracy

In [ ]:

accuracy_score(ytest, y_pred_test)

0.7746803977272727

Our classifier had a 77 percent accuracy, which isn't too bad. However, we want to know further in depth on how and why our classifier work the way it did. We can observe this using a confusion matrix. A confusion matrix is a useful tool for evaluating the performance of a classifier, such as a random forest classifier. It provides a detailed breakdown of the true positive, false positive, true negative, and false negative predictions made by the classifier, allowing us to see where the model is making accurate predictions and where it is making mistakes. This information can be used to identify areas for improvement in the model and to gain a better understanding of its overall performance. For example, if the confusion matrix shows that the classifier is frequently making false positive predictions, we might want to adjust the model or change the way it is being trained to improve its accuracy in that area. Overall, the confusion matrix is a valuable tool for evaluating the performance of a random forest classifier and for identifying areas for improvement. Below we will create a color coded and labeled confusion matrix.

Looking at confusion matrix, recall, precision, and accuracy¶

In [ ]:
# Get and reshape confusion matrix data
matrix = confusion_matrix(ytest, y_pred_test)
matrix = matrix.astype('float') / matrix.sum(axis=1)[:, np.newaxis]

# Build the plot

            cmap=plt.cm.Greens, linewidths=0.2)

# Add labels to the plot
class_names = ['Good', "Poor", "Standard"]

tick_marks2 = tick_marks + 0.5
plt.xticks(tick_marks, class_names, rotation=25)
plt.yticks(tick_marks2, class_names, rotation=0)
plt.xlabel('Predicted label')
plt.ylabel('True label')
plt.title('Confusion Matrix for Random Forest Model')
plt.show()

This confusion matrix represents the performance of a classifier on a three-class classification problem. The rows of the matrix represent the actual class labels, while the columns represent the predicted class labels.

Overall, the classifier appears to be performing quite well, with the majority of the predictions falling on the diagonal of the matrix. This indicates that the classifier is generally making accurate predictions, with most of the predictions falling into the correct class.

Looking more closely at the individual cells of the matrix, we can see that the classifier is making relatively few false positive and false negative predictions. For example, in the first row, only 0.0027 of the predictions for "good" are false positives (predicted as "good" but actually belonging to another class). Similarly, in the second row, only 0.019 of the predictions for "poor" are false negatives (predicted as a different class but actually belonging to "poor"). This suggests that the classifier is generally able to correctly identify the class of most samples.

There are a few areas where the classifier could be improved. For example, in the third row, the classifier is making relatively more false positive predictions for "standard" (0.069), and relatively more false negative predictions for "standard" (0.12). This could be an area for improvement, and further analysis might be necessary to understand why the classifier is struggling in this particular case.

Overall, this confusion matrix suggests that the classifier is performing well, with relatively few false positive and false negative predictions. However, there may be some room for improvement, particularly in the third row of the matrix.

For some more analysis we can take a look into a report of precision, recall, and accuracy. Precision, recall, and accuracy are all metrics used to evaluate the performance of a classifier.

Precision is a measure of the classifier's ability to correctly identify positive samples. It is defined as the number of true positive predictions made by the classifier, divided by the total number of positive predictions made by the classifier. A classifier with high precision is good at minimizing false positive predictions.

Recall is a measure of the classifier's ability to correctly identify all positive samples in a dataset. It is defined as the number of true positive predictions made by the classifier, divided by the total number of actual positive samples in the dataset. A classifier with high recall is good at minimizing false negative predictions.

Accuracy is a measure of the overall performance of a classifier. It is defined as the number of correct predictions made by the classifier, divided by the total number of samples in the dataset. A classifier with high accuracy is making relatively few mistakes overall.

In practice, it is often desirable to have both high precision and high recall, as well as high accuracy. However, these metrics can sometimes trade off against each other, so it is important to carefully consider the specific needs of a particular application when choosing which metrics to optimize.

This classification report provides an evaluation of a classifier on a three-class classification problem. The classes are "Good," "Poor," and "Standard."

Overall, the classifier is performing reasonably well, with an overall accuracy of 0.77. This means that the classifier is correctly predicting the class of 77% of the samples in the dataset.

Looking more closely at the precision, recall, and f1-score for each class, we can see that the classifier is performing best on the "Standard" class, with a precision of 0.78, a recall of 0.81, and an f1-score of 0.79. This suggests that the classifier is relatively good at correctly identifying samples belonging to the "Standard" class.

The classifier is performing somewhat less well on the "Good" class, with a precision of 0.72, a recall of 0.67, and an f1-score of 0.69. This indicates that the classifier is making more mistakes on this class, both in terms of false positive and false negative predictions.

The classifier is performing similarly on the "Poor" class, with a precision of 0.79, a recall of 0.77, and an f1-score of 0.78. This suggests that the classifier is making relatively few mistakes on this class.

Overall, this classification report suggests that the classifier is performing well, but with some room for improvement, particularly on the "Good" class. Further analysis may be necessary to understand why the classifier is struggling in this particular area.
